AccessDescript: From junction of 22 (West Side Road) and 423 (377679X, 4059394Y), turn west on 423 and go 19 mi to the end of 423.  Then follow pack trail into Jumpup Canyon, past Jumpup Spring. This spring is about 1.4 km farther down the and about 140 m up a drainage to the east.
SiteDescription: This small hillslope spring emerges from a colluvial slope in a steep tributary to Jumpup Canyon. It has been manipulated in the past.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from AZ State Land Office layer.

AccessDescript: Directly across (to the East) of Hawaii Spring
SiteDescription: This small hanging garden emerges in an otherwise dry channel.  The runout flows through a dry plunge pool that is filled with gravel.
Georef_Comments: Coordinate shifted based on aerial imagery.

AccessDescript: Private
SiteDescription: This is a heavily anthropogenically altered hillslope springs complex with a concrete source (A) on an excavated source (head of B) and an excavated channel throughout.

AccessDescript: From Deer Lake, drive East on Forest Road 270B about 2.15 mi. Turn left (south) on 270 and continue for 1.57 mi. Turn right on 270T and follow for .86 miles. Then, follow FR 2674 for 12 miles.
SiteDescription:
This spring was included in Brown and Moran study.This heleocrene spring was surveyed by Grand Canyon Trust in July 2010.The spring has multiple orifices was verified by Steve Rice with the National Park Service with a recreation grade GPS.
In 2015, the Springs Stewardship Institute surveyors revisited the site. The first emergence comes from a 1st order channel from which stream flow may occasionally emerge in wet conditions. The flow emerges from the soil near the base of the Kaibab formation. The channel then meanders through the meadow.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from GCT, coordinates from Brown and Moran

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams, travel south on CR-73 for 12.3 mi. Turn left on NF-57 (Bear Springs Rd) for 0.3 mi. Turn right onto NF-4218A and continue south for 0.5 mi. Springs is located 300 m southwest in the bottom of a small canyon.
SiteDescription: This rheocrene spring emerges in a forested cliff-lined canyon and re-emerges downstream, as mapped.
Georef_Comments: GPS readings taken during survey.

SiteDescription: This small ( ca. 35 L/min) rheocrene spring emerges along a fracture line in the Muav Formation flowing into Beaver Canyon Creek.

AccessDescript: From visitor's center, hike down the Aspen Trail to head of Betatakin Canyon access trail. Continue down old trail to bottom of canyon - there is a gate so you need to pick up a key from NPS staff. Spring is in first major alcove to the north, about 20m off the trail. //Note: Channel substrate was recorded during aquatic macroinvertebrate sampling.
SiteDescription: Another spring is located approx. 500 m down canyon at Betatakin Ruin.This spring is located in an overhanging alcove.We surveyed from the alcove to the drip line.The channel continues, but is influenced by overland flow.
Georef_Comments: Position estimated from location marked on topo map.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, west side, Big Springs Canyon, at Big Springs Administrative Site
SiteDescription: This is a contact seepage gushet emerging from the base of the Coconino sandstone and flowing 50 m down a steep talus slope to a NFS station and pond. Larry Stevens has visited this site 3 times, and completed a comprehensive survey in 2005 with RJ Johnson.The source of the location was confirmed with a 1:24K Digital Raster Graphic.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Larry Stevens, adjusted to match DRG as GPS EPE was 26 meters.  The measurement was taken from the side of the base of A.

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams, travel south on County Rd 73 for 7.15 mi. Turn left and head east onto NF-139 (Overland) for 6.4 miles. Turn right onto NF-161 and continue for 0.9 mi before bearing right on Whiting Ranch Rd for 0.3 mi. Turn right onto Overland and continue for 1.5 mi. Spring is located 130 m due south from this location.
SiteDescription: This is a hillslope spring that emerges from boulders in a decomposing basalt flow margin. There is seepage along the base of a steep bank in the drainage. The surrounding area is heavily forested. The source has been manipulated with piping.
Georef_Comments: GPS coordinates were taken at source.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office
AccessDescript: A 1.5 mi walk on a steep, winding trail on the E side of Prospect Canyon near Hundred and Ninetythree Mile Creek.
SiteDescription: This is a fracture controlled contact spring that emerges near the base of the coconino sandstone, in a small drainage. The plunge pool is strongly dominated by surface flow.Big Spring is a source spring.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were estimated by taking the measurement 50 meters SE of site and 70 meters upslope.

AccessDescript: From Munds Park travel east on W Pinewood Blvd to Mormon Lake Rd 5.75 mi. Continue on NF-700 for 0.8 mi before turning right on NF-91 to NF-91B for 1 mi. The spring is located 30 m east from the road on a hillslope 25 m up from the road.
SiteDescription: This site was imported from the SSI geodatabase, a compilation from multiple sources. The spring emerges from cutback along the road bed on FR 91B. Flow runs into a ditch along the road in a ponderosa, aspen, and oak forest.

AccessDescript: Go on 423 and turn right on 236 at 363923X and 4054608Y. Go 40 m and turn south on 201.  Go on 201 for 1.2mi, then turn R(west) on 201A. Then go 3.7 mi on 201A (almost to end).  Pack trail starts at 358255X and 4054296Y. Follow pack trail north, 675 m to Little Spring. Continue following the drainage for 350 m to the site. Follow game trail on canyon left, then drop into the canyon  just above the spring. Elevation difference: 240 m. Spring UTMs were different from UTMs on map.
SiteDescription: This small seepage rheocrene spring emerges from the Hermit Shale channel,  amidst a pile of very large limestone boulders in the upper drainage of Little Spring Canyon, northwest of Little Spring.

AccessDescript: On River right in Sowats Canyon about 360 meters upstream of "Box Elder Spring"  This Spring is tucked up in a small side drainage.  It actually has Box Elders at it.
SiteDescription: Water seeps out of many sites of a large moss covered boulder and flows down a channel at least 50m.
Georef_Comments: G. Rink took GPS coordinates on the ridge to the south they were as follows NAD 27 UTM Zone 12 366933 4045245

AccessDescript: The spring is about 25 meters up the canyon from where it is marked on the DRG, which marks the tank where water has been diverted.
SiteDescription: This is a small alcove at the contact between the Hermit and Toroweap Formations.There does not appear to be Coconino Sandstone here, and the aquifer appears to be in the Toroweap Formation. The site may have been manipulated by adding a berm that forms a pool. The site and pool receive no direct sunlight.

AccessDescript: From exit 157 on I-70, follow Devil Dog Rd for 0.7 mi and turn left on W Pine Springs Rd. for 1.2 mi. Make a sharp left on NF-798 and sharp right on S Hat Rand Rd. Continue south for 2 mi. Turn right on NF-274S for 0.7 mi and make sharp left on NF-42 for 2 mi. Spring is located 200 m due south. Access to this site is on a fairly rough road and the short hike is relatively easy.
SiteDescription: In 2014, Campbell Spring was depicted on the DRG, and was said to be PFC by a surveying hydrologist. It is located in a channel, with several sources emerging from fractured rock. According to Kit Macdonald, the USFS has introduced northern leopard frog here.
Georef_Comments: Averaged x3 in 1 hr

AccessDescript: Drive to Cane Ranch HQ, walk 1.5 km up to base of Coconino following aquiduct/pipe. The springs emerges from a ca. 12 m deep qanat at the Coconino-Hermit contact on creek right.
SiteDescription: The spring was likely once a hanging garden, but not emerges from a 12 m-deep qanat at the Coconino SS-Hermit Shale contact.
Georef_Comments: Taken  outside of overhang near qanat mouth

AccessDescript: This spring is visible from the parking area on the road that runs from the Kane Ranch into the canyon.
SiteDescription: This hanging garden emerges along a 52-m reach at the base of Coconino Sandstone.It drips along the wall, some forming small pools in colluvial slope. The dry backwall with precipitate extends about 2 m above the wet backwall.
Georef_Comments: Taken at base of CS, GPS accuracy +/-S due to difference averaged x$ over 30 mins.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office
AccessDescript: From Cane Ranch headquarters, cross GCT land, go back into very large canyon. Follow it up about a mile. There are 2 springs on left up small side canyon, hard to find. In another mile at end of the canyon, follow pipeline berms to cliff face to springs. These have been heavily developed, bored out into caves.
SiteDescription: This is an anthropogenic cave source that has been impounded in a cave emerging from the base of Coconino sandstone.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from DEM; coordinates from DRG

AccessDescript: May be more easily accessible from below, up Cane Canyon.
SiteDescription: Cane Two Qanats is a contact hanging gardensprings complex at the Coconino SS/Hemit Shale contact at the mouth of Cane Canyon North Fork. Piping in both qanats diverts virtually all flows from these heavily manipulated springs.
Georef_Comments: Elevation and Coordinates from GPS unit

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, west side, in Castle Canyon, one mile south of Big Springs Administrative Site
SiteDescription: This hillslope/hanging garden has been heavily manipulated with a spring box, a trough, and piping.The sources lie beneath an extensive sandstone overhang in a rock shelter. Such an isolation budget should have made the site attractive to prehistoric peoples.
Georef_Comments: GPS was taken at the base of polygon C, as it was not possible to get a reading at the source under the overhang.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, approximately 16 miles south of Jacobs Lake 100 meters east of Hwy 67.
SiteDescription: According to Larry Stevens, this lake may be fed by an ephemeral spring, as it dried up in 2000 and 2002. The spring appears to discharge directly into the lake. There is evidence of overflow into the depression next to the lake, but there is no other outflow channel.
Georef_Comments: lat/long coordinates and elev from USGS

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: From exit 178 on I-40, travel south on County Rd 141 (E Parks Rd) toward Garland Prairie Rd for 0.08 mi. Continue south on S Garland Prairie Rd (CR-141) for 9.14 mi. Turn left and travel 0.58 mi south on S Thomas Loop Rd and park in a small lot.  Hike due west 260 m along a trail then drop into the drainage.
SiteDescription: This named site is located in the headwaters of Sycamore Canyon, emerging from a basalt outcrop on the side of the drainage. Adjacent to the Sycamore trail, it is about 250 m from a small parking area. It is depicted on the DRG, and has been piped. The outflow is subject to surface runoff.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG. Flora survey UTMs were 3890674N, 410222E

AccessDescript: Hermit trail to Dripping Springs trail. Training trip. Vegetation foliar cover was estimated in the field and converted to cover classes in the database. Veg strata cover was estimated from the species cover data (not recorded in the field).
SiteDescription: Dripping springs emerges as a hanging garden type spring from the Coconino Sandstone in the Hermit Creek area.The spring has a sub-aerial emergence environment and the spring orifice type is a contact spring.

AccessDescript: Dustin Burger said these sometimes go dry, but they hold water longer than one would expect. Go down 22, then head south on 226.
SiteDescription: This site was included in the Brown and Moran study (1970s), but is not included on any other layer and is labeled on the DRG as "Dry Park Lakes". It is a natural pond or spring and may or may not be groundwater dependent.It is in a natural depression on the surface of the Kaibab Formation.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were taken from GeoXT.

AccessDescript: From Crystal Spring go to 402730x, 4028046y on the rim, then go down a steep slope about 500 vertical feet.
SiteDescription: This is a hillslope spring on a steep, heavily forested slope. There is a narrow Coconino Sandstone ampitheatre about 100 meters below the source that originates in Toroweap Limestone. Due to the surrounding terrain, this site has receieved very little human visitation. Although it provides much of the base flow of North Canyon Creek, it appears on no maps; nor was it included in any springs layer. It was first located by Glenn Rink in June 2011.

InfoSourceDet: Added based on DRG; ID from AZ Dept. Water Resources GWIS
AccessDescript: Follow highway 89A south from the Pulliam airport exit off of I17 for about 3 miles. You will see a sign to the left for Griffith Spring.
SiteDescription: This is a small restored spring that emerges from the base of a basalt flow, passes through a removed bermed pond, and descends into a low gradient cienega.
Georef_Comments: UTM coordinates and elevation were taken from the USGS DLGs.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office
AccessDescript: This site is only accessible by helicopter.
SiteDescription: Harding is a nearly pristine rheocrene spring emerging from coarse alluvium 70m downstream from a travertine paleo-spring in Harding Canyon.  The spring emerges and flows about 1.5 km through heavy riparian growth.

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams, travel south on County Rd 73 for 12.3 mi. Turn left on NF-57 (Bear Springs Rd) and continue for 0.32 mi before turning right on NF-4218A and traveling south for 0.45 mi. Continue left onto Overland Rd for 0.3 mi. Spring is 430 m due east.
SiteDescription: This rheocrene spring emerges in a small runoff-dominated channel in a heavily forested area.
Georef_Comments: GPS and elevation data taken at the source.

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams, travel south on County Rd 73 for 12.3 mi. Turn left on NF-57 (Bear Springs Rd) and continue for 0.54 mi before turning right on NF-4216A and traveling SE for 0.2 mi. Turn right on NF-4217 and travel south for 0.7 mi. Spring is 150 m due SE.
SiteDescription: This is a small rheocrene hillslope spring. There is some seepage in the channel and some from the bank. 200 m downstream is Hat Tank that is excavated to capture flow.
Georef_Comments: GPS readings taken at uppermost source.

AccessDescript: Go south on Perkinsville Road out of Williams for approximately 7.5 miles.  Take a right turn onto NF 122.  There will be a sign for Twin Springs (actually located at Twin Springs Rd Unnamed) and then road to the south at approximately 4.7 miles from the Perkinsville Road turn.  Continue on Rt 122 past Twin Springs for about 1.5 miles on a rough road. The spring is in Hell Canyon, about 0.2 miles south of where the road takes a sharp turn to the right.
SiteDescription: This site is in a steep, heavily forested drainage.

AccessDescript: Travel west on NF-236 to NF-336 until the road ends at the Horse Spring trail-head. Hike down Horse Canyon on the Horse Spring trail for approximately 2 km. Spring is visible from above but access to the spring is from below within the drainage.
SiteDescription: Seepage emerges from a colluvial slope in the lower member of the Toroweap Formation. There are several small sources that merge into the main channel that is dry upstream, but subject to heavy runoffs.

AccessDescript: Hike on Jumpup trail 0.25 miles from Jumpup trailhead.
SiteDescription: This small hanging garden emerges from the contact between Coconino Sandstone and Hermit Shale, and flows over a travertine wall.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were derived from the DRG; elevations came from the 10m DEM. GPS coordinates were widly variable.

InfoSourceDet: Arizona Dept. Water Resources GWSI db; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: From Williams, AZ go east on I-40 (14.68 mi). At exit 178 take ramp on the right to Parks Rd (0.31mi). Turn right onto S. Garland Prairie Rd (CR 141) (8.12 mi). Turn left/south on Scout Camp Rd(CR 527) (1.04mi). Turn right/west onto S. Thomas Loop Rd (.38 mi). Bear left on power line easement Rd (.63 mi). Make sharp right on Sycamore and go 0.3 mi, where there is an established parking area. Spring is NE.
SiteDescription:
This named site is located in the headwaters of Sycamore Canyon, and is depicted on the DRG. Surveyed by Flora in 2004, it was reported to be a limnocrene spring emerging from a basalt layer. In 2014, SSI surveyors found a
large springs complex with four discreet hillslope sources, and probably diffuse emergence, in a wide, shallow channel, heavily influenced by runoff. The site is in a forested area, within 500 meters of a parking lot. The flow was reported in 1949 as 0.0631 in the Arizona GWSI database.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG.

SiteDescription: This site is located in a pre-existing channel, and is comprised of a pool encircled on three sides by igneous bedrock walls roughly 2 meters high.  There is a plethora of rock art ranging from early Native American to modern graffiti within the area.  On a rock above the northwest corner of the pool is a plaque stating that this site is listed on the National Historic Register.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG.

AccessDescript: Go on 423 and turn right on 236 at 363923X and 4054608Y. Go 40 m and turn south on 201.  Go on 201 for 1.2mi, then turn R(west) on 201A. Then go 3.7 mi on 201A (almost to end).  Follow pack trail from 358255X and 4054296Y  north, 675 m to Little Spring. There's a trail that leads to the spring just below a dry fall.
SiteDescription: This small rheocrene spring emerges in a channel in the base of the lower Toroweap formation. It lies within the Kanab Creek Wilderness boundary.
Georef_Comments: Latitude and longitude from Trimble 60XM; PDOP: 10.5. Elevation was taken from 10m DEM.

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams travel south on County Rd-73 (Perkinsville Rd) for 7.3 mi. Turn right onto E Lockett Springs Ranch Rd and continue for 0.3 mi.
SiteDescription: This site is a pumped and flowing helocrene that feeds into a 2 ha pond.
Georef_Comments: GPS reading was taken at the spring house.

AccessDescript: From junction of 22 and 462, head north on 462, past junction with 230 at 3.5 miles (230 is impassable in 2011), to 762 in 5.5 miles. Turn left on 762 i heading west.In 1.85 miles, turn south on 9081. Go past Cougar lake on right. In 1 mile this road connects with 230. Head southeast on 230 for about a mile. Lookout Lakes spring, mapped by Brown and Moran,  is less than 100 meters to the left of the road.
SiteDescription: This site is not listed as a spring on any other layer, but was listed in the Brown and Moran study as a spring. It is a perennial pond that may be spring supported (limnocrene) and is located in a natural depression on the surface of the Kaibab limestone.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Brown and Moran.

AccessDescript: From exit 178 on I-40, travel north on Parks Rd for 0.15 mi. Turn right onto E Old Highway 66 for 0.5 mi and continue east to NF-2328 for 0.7 mi.
SiteDescription: This site was likely a hillslope spring that has been heavily manipulated over the past century or so. Six tanks have been installed with piping leading to a trough. The site has been heavily logged, probably clear-cut.
Georef_Comments: The GPS coordinates were averaged for 6 minutes at uppermost well containing water.  No specific gps unit information was recorded.

InfoSourceDet: Added based on DRG; ID from AZ Dept. Water Resources GWIS
SiteDescription: This site is a large low gradient cienaga that emerges in a wet meadow surrounded by ponderosa pine forest.The site has been heavily manipulated by a big, non-functional, spring box.A nearby abandoned A-frame house, old fencing, and an Ericameria-Poa pasture surround the spring.Several very old, large, cut stumps of ponderosa pine are on the edge of the pasture.
Georef_Comments: GPS readings were taken at rock collecting box and were averaged at plus or minus 2 meters in 3 minutes.

AccessDescript: Best to visit site before running Lava Falls; access from 179.5L. Go on top of downstream terrace and proceed to base of Muav cliffs downstream. Follow base of cliff through to a distinct pond. Second (middle) pond has obvious water upwelling.
SiteDescription: Because the springs emerge under the historic high water line, land ownership is unresolved. The spring wells up from the base of a Cambrian Muav limestone cliff and flows in a series of small travertine falls to the Colorado River, 100 m away. The complex occurs within a  ~150m wide travertine platform with several large pools, several meters deep.
Georef_Comments: Estimated from spring mark on topo map. Coordinates converted from UTMs

AccessDescript: From Perkinsville Rd, turn W on Coleman Lake Rd, then right (NE) on 780. Follow to 780B, then turn left.
SiteDescription: This site is marked as a tank on the topographic map. Surveyors suspect it is groundwater supported, as it had water during a very dry period in late June 2014.

AccessDescript: From I-40 east, take exit 178, then turn left on Parks Rd. Turn left at stop sign onto Old Route 66, then left on N. Spitz Spring Rd, R on S Spitz Spring Rd, R on Somerset Ranch Rd, then R on 781 J. Follow a bumpy dirt road for about 1 mile; the spring emerges from below the Interstate.
SiteDescription: The spring is a low-graded cienega in a forested area. The source has been built on top of by the creation of Interstate 40.  From the source the water channelizes for approximately 70 meters into a pool.
Georef_Comments: 100 meters upslope from where Mineral Springs was mapped

AccessDescript: Access via the Jumpup - Nail (Sowats) Trail and go down canyon 1 km.
SiteDescription: Two small gushets and additional seepage flow from the contact at the base of the Supai Wescogame formation on creek right. This is the main source; an additional seepage emerges upstream in the channel, and in the colluvial hillslope (D) immediately upslope from the gushets. This spring was  surveyed by Larry Stevens and by GCT in 2009.
Georef_Comments: Coord from DRG; elev from DEM

AccessDescript: From the town of Williams, travels south on County Rd 73 (S Perkinsville Rd) for 11.5 mi. Spring is 500 m due west.
SiteDescription: This helocrene spring emerges from the base of a basalt flow, and would flow/seep broadly across a wet meadow, were it not captured into two spring boxes and piped to a trough.
Georef_Comments: GPS coordinates were taken at the upper spring box.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, the head of and in North Canyon
SiteDescription: Uppermost of three springs in the North Canyon drainage.  This is a small hillslope spring emerging from a steep colluvial slope and flowing about 4 m into North Canyon Creek at base of Coconino formation.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Brown and Moran.

SiteDescription: This is a hillslope spring that emerges from a 0.75 m wide qanat.The spring has been boxed, lined with wood, piped, and channelized.

AccessDescript: Take 462 north to 758, turn left. In about 2 miles turn right on 759. Follow 759 to a fenceline to the north. At the fenceline, there is a 2-track to the south, 9094T. This leads fairly close to spring, about .4 miles.
SiteDescription: This spring has been developed with a cement and metal trough; the box was capped by the USFS.

InfoSourceDet: Imported from USGS Geonames; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: Drive to lower Sycamore Creek Wilderness Area from Tuzigoot Road in Clarkdale. Proceed 3.7 mi upstream alpong Parsons Trail to the uppermost exposure of water in the creek.
SiteDescription: This is a linear series of lentic rheocrenic pools emerging from the upstream dry Sycamore Canyon.The flow emerges where a fracture elevates the Redwall for several tens of meters.

AccessDescript: From West Side Road, take 425 for 6 mi to intersection with 427. Then continue 1.7 mi to junction with 233. Turn right on 233 and go about 5 mi to junction with 657.  Go on 657 for 1.8 mi to the end of the road. Follow pack trail into Sowats Canyon for about 900 m. Go down Sowats Canyon about 3 km.  From 367520x, 4044640y, the spring is about 400 meters northeast up a steep drainage, about 150 meters higher. The middle section has dense vegetation; there might be a route around on the northwest side of the canyon.
SiteDescription: This 60 m long hanging garden emerges from the base of the Coconino sandstone in a small tributary of Sowatts Canyon.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were derived from DRG; elevations are from 10m DEM.

SiteDescription: Springs emerge from base of sand dune blown over short cliff of Navajo sandstone, at top of long wet meadow. The orifice was outside of the runoff channel. This area has been heavily manipulated to support agriculture (2015 comment).
AKA: Susungua, Tupqa, Pasture Wash Spring lower, Shalako lower
Georef_Comments: GPS coordinates

AccessDescript: Go north on West Side Road out of the forest to some road (374441X, 4071435Y). Go on this road for 4 mi. Continue straight on BLM 164 at 369183X and 4069052Y.  Go 1.5 mi to 367047X, 4067840Y. Turn southeast on BLM 165 and go 0.6 mi to 367806X, 4067230Y. Then turn right and go southwest on BLM D166. Follow this road for about 2.6mi and look for a way into the canyon on your left (south). The spring is 550 m straight south in that canyon. Difference in elevation: 150m.  Access requires downclimbing a boulder.
SiteDescription: This is a tiny, heavily manipulated hanging garden that emerges from a fracture in the Toroweap Limestone. Solar radiation includes an additional 30 minutes in the late afternoon of March and September.
Georef_Comments: Elev from 10 m DEMs. No GPS recording was possible at site.

AccessDescript: From Camp Navajo, go to igloo 215.
SiteDescription: This spring is marked on the DRG and included in the NHD Database. It is in a heavily developed area within the military reservation boundary.  This is a piped spring that emerges under a gravel road and flows into one of two troughs, then 50 m into a LGC.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG and NHD Database.  GPS coordinates were 150 m SSE, 421723x, 3898897y.

AccessDescript: Starting at Parks, Arizona, go south on CR-141 (N Spring Valley Rd E) toward E Old Highway 66 for 0.05 miles. Turn left at E Old Highway 66 to stay on CR-141 (E Old Highway 66) for 0.56 miles. Turn right at E Old Highway 66/Brannigan Park Rd to stay on CR-141 (N Parks Rd) for 0.13 miles. Turn right onto ramp and go on I-40 W/AZ-89 S for 6.29 miles. At exit 171 take ramp on the right to Pittman Valley Rd/Deer Farm Rd for 0.33 miles. Turn left on Pittman Valley Rd (E Deer Farm Rd) and drive for 0.64 miles. Turn right on N Good Ln for 0.24 miles. Bear right on E 4H Club Camp Rd for 0.35 miles. Turn left and go 0.39 miles. Turn left and go 0.39 miles. Finish at Pitman Valley Unnamed Spring on the left.
SiteDescription: This site is not depicted on the DRG, although there are several tanks marked in the area. It is included in the NHD Database. This site was likely a wet meadow that has been excavated and perhaps lined. The site area is large and open with no trees.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from NHD Database.

AccessDescript: Travel up Keams Canyon road several miles.
SiteDescription: This rheocrenic limnocrene, with an anthropogenic concrete spring box, emerges on the edge of the Keams Canyon floodplain. The substrate consists of clayey sand alluvium that is probably fed from the Toreva aquifer.

This is a rheocrene spring that is likely a secondary emergence from Quartermaster Travertine Dome Spring which is located about 2 km upstream.The data came from USGS Quad, and the site was verified by 1:24 Digital Raster Graphic.The field has not been confirmed.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates and elevation were taken from 3/24/2013 survey.  Toughbook coordinates on same day were 35 57' 47" -113 45' 49"

AccessDescript: From Diamond Creek/Peach Springs Road at 3 km up from Peach Springs in Peach Springs Wash.  The spring is on creek left 120 km from road at the base of a 3 m cutbank.
SiteDescription: This spring is an excavated hillslope spring with a 3 m deep qanat and a concrete door frame.  The spring emerges along a contact line in cemented colluvium.

AccessDescript: From 419412x 4061372y on Alt 89A turn S, (4960?) in 1.8 miles take left fork,2.8 miles to end of rd nr Cram Ranch, turn left. In .2 miles turn right. In .9 miles keep left. In about 3.4 miles turn left (north). Road should end in 1.5 miles, pointed straight toward side drainage. Walk about 80 meters to meet drainage and turn ds (east). Spring is about 3.3 km down drainage. Requires some rock climbing.
SiteDescription: Small contact spring in bottom of bedrock drainage.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates and elev estimatedfrom DRGs & DEMs. Unable to obtain GPS signal from site.

AccessDescript: Main source in Snake gulch
SiteDescription: This spring provides a main source of flow in Snake Gulch. Several seeps (A & B) emerge and contribute flow into a well-defined channel.It was surveyed by Larry Stevens in 11/2009.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM and coordinates from DRG, both confirmed by GPS.

AccessDescript: From exit 167 on I-40 travel south on S Garland Prairie Rd for 7 mi. Turn right onto NF-18 and continue for 1.6 mi. Hike 600 m due west up drainage.
SiteDescription: This is a low gradient cienega that has been excavated. A 3-m well has been rocked-in and piped into a bermed pond. The site is 150 m from where it is mapped on the DRG. The total area in 2016 was about 379.5 sq. meters.
Georef_Comments: GPS readings taken where pipe emerges; 2016 survey confirms location

InfoSourceDet: Added based on DRG layer; ID from AZ Dept of Water Resources GWIS
AccessDescript: West Central AZ Strip, Uinkaret Plateau area, one mile north of Toroweap overlook in Saddle Horse Canyon at 174.9 Mile Right.
SiteDescription: The site was verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: lat/long coordinates from USGS

AccessDescript: From junction 22 (west side road) and 423 (377679X, 4059394Y). Turn west on 423 and go 1.7 mi to 235. Turn right on 235 and go west 7 mi to 267. Turn northwest at 368526X 4058167Y onto 267. On 267, go 2.8 mi. At 365063X and 4059998Y, turn southwest on 267C. Go 3.4 mi to the end of the road. Near the end of the road, a pack trail heads northeast and into the drainage, and passes by slide spring. Distance: 1.4 km. Elevation difference: 200 m. Healy and Rice directions: Hike from Slide Point, down scree, to right looking straight out from point.  A thick willow patch can be seen from point.
SiteDescription: This small rheocrene emerges from beneath a large limestone boulder and flows down a channel over and alongside a large paleo spring travertine mound.
Georef_Comments: Elevations were from 10m DEM, coordinates from the DRG. Coordinates were confirmed by GPS during a site visit. NPS coordinates are NAD27 360429E 4057864N

AccessDescript: From West Side Road, take 425 for 6 mi to intersection with 427. Then continue 1.7 mi to junction with 233. Turn right on 233 and go about 5 mi to junction with 657.  Go on 657 for 1.8 mi to the end of the road. Follow pack trail into Sowats Canyon for about 900 m. Go down Sowats Canyon about 3 km.  From 367520x, 4044640y, the spring is about 600 meters northeast up a steep drainage, about 150 meters higher. Elevation difference is 400 meters to the bottom of the side drainage. The middle section has dense vegetation; there might be a route around on the northwest side of the canyon.
SiteDescription: This is a small hanging garden at the Coconino sandstone-Hermit shale contact with two small travertine half columns.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were estimated from the DRG and GPS, which had a high error due to the terrain; elevations were taken from a 10-meter DEM.

SiteDescription: This is formerly a rheocrene/helocrene spring in Spring Canyon that has been excavated and tanked. It was included in the Brown and Moran study.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM; coordinates from Brown & Moran

AccessDescript: From BLM Rd 8910 off hwy 89A, past Kane Ranch to AGFD Wildlife HQ, follow sign to South Canyon trailhead; descend about 500 meters to South Canyon, downstream about 250 m to the oak grove (not the willow stand, which is ephemeral)
This spring is not accessible from below.
SiteDescription: This spring, located within a Wilderness area, was surveyed by RJ Johnson et al for Grand Canyon Wildlands Council in 2000.The site emerges under a rock on a steep slope, which is heavily forested. The outflow pours into the floor of the canyon.

AccessDescript: Access is the same as Sowats spring. Head down the trail and climb a steep bank on creek right.
SiteDescription: This hillslope spring was surveyed by RJ Johnson et al for Grand Canyon Wildlands Council in 2000 as Sowats B. This site is located on a steep, rocky slope.It is a steep, hillslope seep that emerges through gravelly colluvium, dropping over several ledges into Sowats Canyon.The flow emerges from multiple sources.The field was not confirmed.
Georef_Comments: Elevation and coordinates taken during 2012 survey.

AccessDescript: 6 km up Stone Creek (Colorado River Mile 132R) at top of flow.
SiteDescription: This is a large, complex steep hillslope spring that seeps or flows out of multiple sites. This point is associated with Stone Creek 2 (14255)and Steamboat Center (19570) that are included in the NHD database.
Georef_Comments: Elev. 909m

AccessDescript: This spring is near the base of North Canyon Loop Trail.  We found water pouring across the trail and went up the drainage about 250 m to base of Coconino Sandstone.  The seepage emerges downstream from a 4 m Coconino Sandstone Cliff.
SiteDescription: This small rheocrene emerges at the base of the Coconino Sandstone.  The flow accumulates from the source and is at full flow a few meters downstream.
Georef_Comments: GPS taken at source.

AccessDescript: From junction of Highway 67 and West Side Road, go 3 miles east on Route 611.  Hike down N. canyon loop trail to near base of canyon.  Follow canyon to the right about 200 meters.  The spring is another 200 meters up a side canyon to the right.
SiteDescription: This small seep emerges from the base of Coconino Sandstone in an otherwise dry steep channel.The flow goes underground and re-emerges several times down the drainage for about 200 meters to the trail.This site was verified by a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: GPS coordinates and elevation were taken at the point of first emergence and confirmed within 3 meters with Trimble GeoXT.

AccessDescript: From junction 22 (west side road) and 423 (377679X, 4059394Y). Turn west on 423 and go 3.5 mi to 235. Turn right on 235 and go west 4 mi to 237. Turn right (north) on 237 and go about 1.6 mi. Head of canyon is on the right. Hike down drainage 3 km; spring is in the drainage. Elevation difference is 240 m.
SiteDescription: This small southwest facing hanging garden emerges near the bottom of a steep drainage. It emerges in the lower Toroweap formation.
Georef_Comments: Due to the overhanging ledge above the spring source, GPS measurements were not possible.  Coordinates and elevation were estimated from the DRG and the 10 m DEM.

AccessDescript: Park boats at Tapeats Creek, hike trail up Tapeats Creek (approx. 1.5 miles to the junction with Thunder River). Follow the trail up Thunder River (approx. 1.5 mi) to orifice of Thunder River.
SiteDescription: This spring has multiple orifices emerging from fractures at the Redwall/Muav contact.
Georef_Comments: Position from Brown and Moran

AccessDescript: Heading south from Flagstaff on Interstate 17, take the Kachina Exit. Turn right, then take another immediate right onto Tovar Trail. Go about a mile, past the meadow on the left and up a hill. Nearly at the top of the hill, the spring is on a hillslope on the right.

Drive up Warm Springs canyon on 462.  South of the road there's a million gallon tank. Above the road, on the north side, is an old shack. The shack is the spring. This is the primary water source for Jacob Lake.
SiteDescription: According to USFS, this is a spring with little or no riparian vegetation.The site was surveyed by Grand Canyon Wildlands Council in 2000.The main spring is a qanat with piping at the Coconino/Hermit contact.
Georef_Comments: Elev from 10 m DEM

AccessDescript: The site is located on the central Kaibab Plateau, west side, in Quaking Aspen Canyon. Hike approximately 150 ft up slope from FR 206.
SiteDescription: Small contact spring, visited by Grand Canyon Wildlands Council (2002). This is a rheocrene, hillslope spring and again was surveyed by Grand Canyon Trust in 2010.This site has been verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM; Coordinates from LES and DRG. UTM North Coordinate from GCT.

AccessDescript: Please examine a map closely before proceeding to this site. Some of the roads listed below may be closed or not accessible. Take County Rd 73 (S Perkinsville Rd) south from Williams, AZ to Forest Rd 57. Turn left on FR 57 (Bear Springs Rd). Turn right onto FR 4216A (Overland Rd), then right onto FR 4218G, then right onto FR 417H (to stay on FR 4218G. Turn right onto FR 4219. Continue on FR 4219A for ~0.6 miles. Spring is south of the road, approximately 0.25 miles.
SiteDescription: This rheocrene spring emerges from a basalt flow in a primarily bedrock runoff-dominated channel in a rocky-forested canyon.
Georef_Comments: GPS readings were taken during site visit.

SiteDescription: This spring emerges from a basalt flow at the head of Wild Horse Canyon. The area is heavily forested, and above the cliff-lined section of the canyon.
Georef_Comments: GPS was recorded at upper end of the site.

AccessDescript: Go north on West Side Road out of the forest to some road (374441X, 4071435Y). Go on this road for 4 mi. Continue straight on BLM 164 at 369183X and 4069052Y.  Go 1.5 mi to 367047X, 4067840Y. Turn southeast on BLM 165 and go 0.6 mi to 367806X, 4067230Y. Then turn right and go southwest on BLM D166. Follow this road for about 2.6mi and look for a way into the canyon on your left (south).  Follow the drainage downstream about 1.4 km. Access requires downclimbing a boulder. At 364800X, 4064640Y go up drainage to the left about 500 m to the site. The UTMs were different from the UTMs on the map. The site is about 100 m DS from where it is marked on the DRG (at that point on the DRG, there is no spring).
SiteDescription: This springemerges from a contact in the steep, narrow Wildband Canyon, and flows down the canyon to Snake Gulch. This is a large seepage area on the left side of the canyon.

AccessDescript: South/inner side of Nankoweap Canyon, approximately 1 mile from the Colorado River at river mile 52 on creek right.
SiteDescription: 1 Mile Spring pours out of the fracture directly into the creek.This site has been verified by Steve Rice with the National Park Service, with a recreation grade GPS. He also did a survey of this site.
Georef_Comments: Very high EPE with GPS; elevation calculated from point on DEM

AccessDescript: From Jacob Lake head west on 461/462 past Warm Springs, about 13 km to intersection with Ryan Road. Turn left (south). In 3 km turn right (west) on Nail?.  In about 2 km from road to Sowats point, at 363321e, 4040188n, follow pack trail. After about 3 km the trail nears the creek. The spring is in the bottom of the drainage.
SiteDescription: This tiny rheocrene seep emerges under a Gooddings willow 100 m SE of the larger stand of fremont cottonwood that is conspicuous in the overall drainage. This is likely a secondary emergence from springs exposed in the Coconino sandstone above.Larry Stevens surveyed the site in the fall of 2009.
Georef_Comments: NPS coordinates were NAD 27 361658E 4040635N

AccessDescript: This site is 20 m downstream from the confluence of North Canyon Creek with Crystal Spring Creek. The site is on creek left at the floor of North Canyon.
SiteDescription: This site was surveyed by Larry Stevens in 2000, and included in Brown and Moran study. It was formerly refered to as Larkspur spring. This is a hillslope spring that emerges (possibly secondarily) from colluvial boulders and gravels and flows into North Canyon creek.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates and elevation were taken during 2012 survey.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, three miles southwest of Kaibab Lodge
SiteDescription: According to Larry Stevens, this lake may or may not be spring-fed.
Georef_Comments: coordinates from DRG.  GCT UTMs (8/1/10): 397095East, 4025729North.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, west side, in Indian Hollow Canyon
SiteDescription: This named spring was surveyed by RJ Johnson et al (Grand Canyon Wildlands Council) in 2000.The site has a well, 1.22 m in diameter, with corrugated metal around concrete.The site was verified by the USFS with a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG and AZ State Land Office shapefile.

AccessDescript: Hike down old access trail or currently used trail to Betatakin Ruin. //Note: Channel substrate was recorded during aquatic macroinvertebrate sampling.
SiteDescription: This site is under a very large alcove (75 m high).Several other driplines and hanging gardens are under the alcove within 200 m.This spring emerges as a flowing stream on a hillside.It flows for about 6 m.
Georef_Comments: Position estimated from marked topo map.

SiteDescription: This spring is marked very lightly on the DRG, in the upper reaches of the same drainage as Sowats Spring, about 550 meters upstream. We believe this was surveyed by RJ Johnson et al for Grand Canyon Wildlands Council in 2000 as Sowats A.This site is an alcove with extensive travertine formation covered with moss.The field has not been confirmed.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates and elevation were originally from DEM and DRG and were confirmed via a site visit with the GPS unit.

AccessDescript: From exit 167 on I-40, travel south on S Garland Prairie Rd (NF-141) for 7 mi. Turn right on NF-18 and continue for 0.3 mi. Spring is located 180 m due west.
SiteDescription: This is a medium-sized helocrene spring that has been manipulated and piped. There is a well upslope of spring and troughs below and to the right.
Georef_Comments: GPS coordinates taken at the upper end of the site.

AccessDescript: The springs flow intercepts the Tonto Trail approximately 0.5 km east of Pipe Creek on the Tonto platform 2 km west of the South Kaibab trail. Access to the source upslope through the sawgrass is challenging.
SiteDescription: A rheocrene springs that emerges in a shallow drainage from the Bright Angel shale, flowing for 200m before dropping over the Tapeats Formation and into Pipe Springs Canyon.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2010 from NHD Database; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: Turn east off of Antares Rd.
SiteDescription: This site is a rheocrene with a qanat 14 m deep creating a rheocrenic spring brooke.

AccessDescript: The runout from this spring is very close to the North Canyon trail. However, access to the source would be difficult.
SiteDescription: This is an unmapped fracture spring near the North Canyon trail. The flow emerges from an inaccessible area on an overhanging cliff. It could be a secondary emergence.
Georef_Comments: No GPS reading could be taken at the source because it was too overhung.  The GPS coordinates and elevation were estimated using the topo map and the last known GPS position.

AccessDescript: From Sowats Point, go down trail #8 to Sowats Canyon.  Go upstream in Sowats Canyon approximately 200yds to major drainage from southeast (Bitter Springs drainage).  Go upstream about 20 minutes; large alcove present on stream right.
SiteDescription: This site is in a wide canyon of Sowats, near Bitter Spring. This is a rheocrene spring with multiple orifices.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG. Coordinates confirmed by GCT.

AccessDescript: Take creek left channel up at the fork about 200 meters to alcove.
SiteDescription: This spring is a 40 meter diameter hanging garden/plung pool.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, one mile south of Kaibab Lodge on Hwy 67
SiteDescription: According to Larry Stevens, this lake may be fed by an ephemeral spring.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from GPS, confirmed with 10m DEM. Coordinates from LES, converted from NAD-27.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, North Canyon and East Rim View Point area
SiteDescription: According to Larry Stevens, this lake may be fed by an ephemeral spring.
Georef_Comments: Check location with LES

InfoSourceDet: Dr. Lawrence Stevens data; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: The site is 0.7m south of I17 approximately 1km east of Bellmont.  Exit I40 west of Flagstaff.
SiteDescription: This site is an excavated pond with a 2m berm fed by slow seepage from a springs source in the Upper Kaibab Limestone.

AccessDescript: In Fern Glen Canyon, approximately 0.25 miles from the Colorado River at river mile 168

From Flagstaff take 40 West, a right on 64 North, and the site is approximately 2.7 miles up the highway on the right shoulder. The spring is 10 meters inland from the highway. It is 156 paces past a sign that reads "Passing Lane 500 ft.
SiteDescription: This named site is depicted on the DRG. This site consists of a large pipe in the ground with a circular man-hole type cover over a cylindrical vertical culvert that is 80 cm wide in diameter with water in it. The site is eight meters from Hwy 64. There are four pipes on the inside of the cylindrical tank.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG

InfoSourceDet: Imported from USGS Geonames; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: FR 527 next to road - (sign)
From exit 167, travel SE on Garland Prairie Rd for 6.7 mi. Spring is 665 m due NE.
SiteDescription: This is a dewatered helocrene with a dry spring box where flow apparently emerged from the base of a basalt flow in a semi-fenced ponderosa pine glade.
Georef_Comments: The GPS readings were taking at the springbox.  The Earthmate readings were averaged for 3 minutes and confirmed with the Toughbook.

InfoSourceDet: Imported from USGS Geonames; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: From US-89, exit onto E Elden Springs Rd )NF-556) and travel west for 2 mi. Spring is 85 m due SW.
SiteDescription: This site was imported from the geodatabase, a compilation from multiple sources.The seepages emerge from rhyolite, forming a pool at the base of a cliff. Larry Stevens has visited this site at least 10 times at different times of year, and reports that there has always been water. Cut stumps, fencing, piping, and a concrete tank below indicate long term historic use.
Georef_Comments: Surveyors were unable to get a GPS reading at the source. Coordinates were taken 3 meters NE. On maps the spring is marked at the tank rather than the source.

AccessDescript: Go on 423 and turn right on 236 at 363923X and 4054608Y. Go 40 m and turn south on 201. Go on 201 for 1.2mi, then turn R(west) on 201A. Then go 3.7 mi on 201A (almost to end) to the pack trail at 358255X and 4054296Y. Follow pack trail north, 675 m to Little Spring. Continue following the drainage for about 400 m.This spring is about 125 m up a drainage to the northeast.
SiteDescription: This is a very small rheocrene in the bottom of the upper drainage of Little Spring Canyon, northwest of Little Spring.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM; coordinates from DRG & NHD. Coordinates were confirmed with a GPS.

AccessDescript: Road goes directly to Locust Spring.  In 2010 many down trees made the road impassable.
SiteDescription: This spring is at the end of a FS road in Locust Canyon. Included in Brown and Moran study.This is a heleocrene spring that has multiple orifices.This spring was surveyed by Grand Canyon Trust in May 2010.This site was confirmed using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from DEM; coordinates from Brown and Moran.  Coordinates confirmed by GCT.

SiteDescription: This is a small standing pool of approximately 0.5 square meters that empties into a 20 + meter deep qanat.
Georef_Comments: There was an extra digit in the northing. The datasheet read 39577691.  Extra 7 was removed?

AccessDescript: From 223 Road, watch for old logging road on the right and follow for approximately 1/2 mile.  Then, cut to the right and walk off trail down steep slope.  The spring that surveyors visited was approximately 160 ft from map location.
SiteDescription: The coordinates were provided by Larry Stevens. This is a gushette and rheocrene spring.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Larry Stevens. Confirmed by GCT.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office
AccessDescript: Unnamed tributary of an unnamed tributary of White Ruin Wash, a tributary of Moencopi Wash.
SiteDescription: This site is a hanging garden seeping from the lower dakota sandstone formation.
AKA: Danger (this is probably erroneously marked as on topo), Handprint
Georef_Comments: reading was taken downstream of the plunge pool.

AccessDescript: The site is 1.7 miles north of Big Springs Administration area, about 750 meters from West Side Road.  From the Mangum Camp, go past the buildings and follow the creek up to a pipeline going 100 m upslope to the top of Coconino Sandstone.  Go up the west side of the drainage.
SiteDescription: This is one of five springs surrounding Mangum springs that are depicted on the DRG.It is located 100 m up creek to the top of the Coconino Sandstone.This site has been verified by a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: This site was difficult to get to.

AccessDescript: From Bill Williams Loop road, follow the drainage downstream about 350 m. There is a nice sheep trail on canyon left that will take you to the bottom.
SiteDescription: The spring appears to discharge out of basalt into a pool. There is no visible source. The pool is located in a major drainage channel that is heavily influenced by surface flow.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG and NHD Database.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: The site is located 11 miles north of the community of Peach Springs on the Hualapai Reservation.
SiteDescription: The spring discharge is captured in a concrete box. The soil saturation below this structure has a surface area of approximately 20 feet by 10 feet. The dominant vegetation around this spring site is mesquite Bosque and covers an area of about 100 yards by 200 yards.
Georef_Comments: coordinates estimated from DEMs and AGIC data files

AccessDescript: The spring is located about 10 miles south east from Peach Springs and west of the Lime Stone area.
SiteDescription: Located in a tributary of Peach Springs Canyon. Historically this site was used by bands of Hualapai for farming and consumption. This spring is surrounded by mesquite and willow trees. The spring issues out from vegetation under a willow tree. The spring is a source of drinking water for wildlife and feral Burros. In 1998, feral Burros were captured and removed from around the area. The Burro impacts to the spring site were multiple trailing, distortion of vegetation, and fecal contamination of the water. Since the removal of the Burros from this spring site, there has been visible rejuvenation to the surrounding area with less trailing and increased re-growth of the damaged vegetation. The spring runs year round and has deep pools surrounded by very dense vegetation.

AccessDescript: Park in a turnout along Highway 89 about 100 m upstream of the site and walk down into the drainage.
SiteDescription: Flow emerges between Highway 89 and Oak Creek, in an overflow channel adjacent to the creek. The surrounding area is heavily overgrown with mature trees. It is located near the type locality for Moribaetis mimbresaurus, a rare endemic mayfly species.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, approximately 6.5 miles south of Jacobs Lake off of Hwy 67
SiteDescription: Murray Lakes consists of two anthropogenic ponds that GCWC suspected are springfed because they didn't dry up in dry years. Dustin Burger said they do dry up, and that people haul water in during dry years.
Georef_Comments: lat/long coordinates and elev from USGS. UTMs from DRG. Elevation from DEM.

AccessDescript: From West Side Road, go through the locked gate (permission required), and about 600 meters through the developed area. A small, little used, and heavily overgrown trail leads downcanyon, angling up the hillslope.
SiteDescription: At this site there is a large seeping wall with a large travertine formation in the Toroweap Limestone.The site was verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were taken within 2 meters of the source, and under an overhang.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, the head of and in North Canyon
SiteDescription: This spring is the lowermost of three springs in a steep area of Upper North Canyon, visited by Larry Stevens and included in the Brown and Moran study. The slope above the spring is 44 degrees.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Brown and Moran and DEM.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, the head of and in North Canyon
SiteDescription: This is the middle of three springs in a steep area of North Canyon, visited by Larry Stevens and included in the Brown and Moran study.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Brown and Moran.

AccessDescript: Take I-17 south to the Kachina Road exit. Turn right, then take another immediate right onto Tobar Trail. Park on the side of the road. Cross the meadow to a drainage. Follow the drainage to the right, up towards the spring.
Central Kaibab Plateau, west side, in Parissawampitts Canyon
SiteDescription: This spring has been enclosed in a concrete box. This site has been verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM and confirmed by USGS; coordinates from DRG. Coordinates from GCT survey were similar.

AccessDescript: Central Kaibab Plateau, west side, in Quaking Aspen Canyon. West on West Side Rd .5 miles, turn left on 270T. In 1 mile continue on 222 5 miles. Turn south on 206, and continue 5 miles. Turn right on 3026. Site is about 3 miles down this road, less than 100 meters to the right.
SiteDescription: This contact/fracture hillslope spring was surveyed by Grand Canyon Wildlands Council, included in the Brown and Moran study, and surveyed by Grand Canyon Trust in 2010.The site was verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Elevation and Coordinates from GCT.

InfoSourceDet: Imported from USGS Geonames; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: From exit 178 on I-40 travel south on S Garland Prairie Rd (CR-141) for 8.13 mi. Turn left onto S Boy Scout Camp Rd (CR-527) and continue for 2.16 mi.
SiteDescription: This spring emerges as a hillslope at the base of a basalt flow and feeds a low gradient cienega.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2013 from NHD Database; Location refinement and suvey data from Boris Poff
Georef_Comments: 2.13 PDOP

AccessDescript: Begin from US 89-ALT and head south on Buffalo Ranch Rd. for 1.42 mi. Continue on BLM 249 for 1.95 mi. Go through gate before reaching residence and follow the fense line on 252 to a wash. Hike 4.5 mi up the wash. The spring is not visible from the bottom of the canyon, but is located on the north side, uphill from the main wash.
SiteDescription: This named spring is depicted on the DRG. Coordinates were provided by the AZ State Land Office. Surveyed on June 23, 2015 by SSI, the seepage emerges along a contact between Coconino sandstone and Hermit Shale. A large overhanging ledge shades the site completely along most of the colluvial slope. The site has been manipulated with pipes but not dewatered.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from DRG.

AccessDescript: For Hermit's Rest parking area hike 4 km down the Hermit trail to a shade station.
SiteDescription: This site has a hillside emergence from the Supai, Base of Esplanade. There are multiple spring orifices, no other springs nearby. This site has been manipulated over many years to provide water for hikers on the Hermit trail. There are old pipes and a trough. Seepage emerges from a steep slope above the trail. Flow continues below the lower trail and over the cliffs below.
Georef_Comments: NPS Coordinates are 389952 3991310 (NAD 83) taken at the orifice with a garmin etrex vista.

AccessDescript: From Mormon Lake Rd (CR-90) turn onto NF-90H and travel SW for 2.9 mi. Turn onto NF-219B and continue for 1.6 mi. Turn onto NF-91 and head NW for 1 mile. Spring is 120 m due SW.
SiteDescription: This site was imported from the SSI geodatabase, a compilation from multiple sources. This spring emerges from a hillslope into a broad meadow. It has been extensively modified, with all flow captured in a constructed tank. Flow emerges from a broken pipe 400 m downslope of the site.

AccessDescript: Shultz Pass-Lockett Meadow Rd elevation 2633 meters (8639 ft). From Shultz Pass-Lockett Meadow Rd travel on foot west toward the Interior Valley and Inner Basin along old NF-552 to old NF-552C. Spring is located 3.5 miles from Shultz Pass-Lockett Meadow Rd. Spring elevation 3369 meters (11054 feet).
SiteDescription: Snowslide Spring is a relatively large rheocrenic helocrene. Flow emerges broadly across a rather steep (high-gradient cienega) slope at the base of a rhyolitic (?) wall, and seeps into a channel. Flow first emerges at a discrete point and accumulates over distance downstream.

This is a rheocrene spring at the base of a Coconino Sandstone overhang in a steep northeasterly facing valley. The source is protected by a padlocked steel door. Parts of the channel were dry.This site has been verified using a 1:24K Digital Raster.

AccessDescript: Drive road to livestock trough. Walk up canyon; spring is inside fenced area.
SiteDescription: This named spring is depicted on the DRG. Coordinates were provided by Larry Stevens.This hillslope spring was surveyed by Grand Canyon Trust in 2010.This site was confirmed with a 1:24K Digital Raster.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM; coordinates from LES and DRG. Confirmed by GCT.

AccessDescript: From exit 320 on I-17 travel SE onto Schnebly Hill Rd (NF-226) for 2.7 mi. Turn left onto NF-226B and continue to the right on NF-9468K for 0.8 miles. The site is located above a large fenced meadow.
SiteDescription: This spring has been heavily excavated and manipulated over time. The upper hillslope section has been excavated and diverted, forming a berm between it and the helocrene below. The helocrene has been fenced, but the fence is no longer effective. On the upper end, the fencing is below the berm. The trench circles around the fence line, with one channel returning to the meadow.
Georef_Comments: averaged GPS reading

InfoSourceDet: Dr. Lawrence Stevens data; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: Go to northeast side of Camp Navajo in Tapan Spring Recreation Area.
SiteDescription: This site is an excavated, culvert source that seaps into three excavated ponds on the northeast side of Camp Navajo.  The spring lies in a Ponderosa Pine meadow used for recreation and hunting.
Site was visited by LES et al in 2005 for Grand Canyon Wildlands Council, and was included in Brown and Moran study.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates from Brown & Moran; Elevation from 10m DEM

AccessDescript: About 190 meters upslope and 85 meters higher than Tater Canyon spring (Brown and Moran), in a drainage to the northwest.
SiteDescription: There are at least two sources in the area.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from DEM; coordinate from NHD

AccessDescript: On West Side Rd go south of junction with 423 about .65 miles. Spring is east of the road about 450 meters. Look for small side canyon on east side. A small 2-tracker that looks like it isn't going anywhere leads to the spring. It's developed; there might be 2 springs.
SiteDescription: This is a seeping hillslope spring emerging from Hermit Shale but likely derived from Coconino Sandstone.

Sources are on a south-facing 25m wide travertine wall. There are three gushets, an alcove with an over hanging cliff and rounded wall. There is cave and a shallow 2x4m sandy water area. The site consists of travertine/reservoir and lake habitat.

AccessDescript: From junction 22 (west side road) and 423 (377679X, 4059394Y). Turn west on 423 and go 1.7 mi to 235. Turn right on 235 and go west 7 mi to 267. Turn northwest at 368526X 4058167Y onto 267. On 267, go 2.8 mi. At 365063X and 4059998Y, turn southwest on 267C. Go 3.4 mi to the end of the road. Near the end of the road, a pack trail heads northeast and into the drainage, and passes by slide spring. Follow the drainage down the remains of a paleospring to a stand of Cottonwoods in the bottom of Slide Canyon, then up a drainage to the north to above the highest Cottonwood.
SiteDescription: This small seep emerges from colluvium about 50 meters above the floor of Slide Canyon.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates were estimated from the DRG; elevations came from the 10m DEM. There was no GPS reading at the site.

AccessDescript: Take Coconino County Rd 3 (Lake Mary Rd) south from Flagstaff for approximately 30.6 miles. The spring is west of CR-3 approximately 0.45 miles.
SiteDescription: This site was imported from the SSI geodatabase, a compilation from multiple sources. The spring discharges out of a basalt outcrop into a bermed stock tank. There is typically no flow beyond the stock tank. Previous surveyors reported Pinus Ponderosa revegetation /encroachment near the spring.  There is no path to the spring (a road berm blocks view).

InfoSourceDet: Imported from USGS Geonames; Other DB from AZDWR
AccessDescript: From Highway 180, turn north up Snowbowl Road. Hike along signed trail (Viet Springs Trail) for .08 km, and go to upper west side of homestead site to colorful basalt cliffs. Two small caves are present here.
SiteDescription: This fracture spring emerges from a basalt flow. There is much Indian art around the source.

AccessDescript: From NF 237 park short of Willow Point at 36.70647, -112.50703 (WGS 84). Hike down a ridge to the creek bed at 36.70304, -112.51059. Then follow the creek downstream about 1.8 km.
SiteDescription: Seepage emerges along a contact in the lower Toroweap Formation for about 100 m on the left side of Willow Canyon. It is not noted on any maps. A cottonwood and a stand of willows is about 50 m downstream. There is also an old crushed metal tank near the willows, indicating past use. The lower part of the source area is subject to occasional flooding.

SiteDescription: This is depicted on the DRG as a lake; however, the survey crew suspects that it is heavily influenced by groundwater after examination of the surrounding soils and water table. On 8/22/2015, the survey crew noted this site as a lacustrine/palustrine wetland near Hwy 69. The site is surrounded by spruce and aspen.
Georef_Comments: NPS Coordinates were NAD27 12 398982E 4033980N.  Elevation was 8820 Feet

AccessDescript: Approximately 1  miles west of Milkweed spring in a parallel drainage.
SiteDescription: West water spring is a series of several pools in the coarse basaltic gravels of West water Canyon at an elevation of 4800 feet. The exact source of the outflow is not determined, as it apparently lies under gravels in the streambed. The stream flow changes during the seasons, but continues to flow year round. Improvements to Buck and Doe Road have affected the west side of the canyon by constructing a steep embankment where filling has been placed to remove a dip in the road. The streambed itself has not been affected and is in its natural position, except in the lower portion below the main pools where construction activities disturbed the streambed.

There are 2 small pools above the source. A dry drainage channel comes in upstream of the source and there are ruins of a historic cabin nearby. SSI was informed that archaeology at the site is monitored by the Arizona Site Stewards (volunteer site monitoring with Arizona State Parks).

AccessDescript: The site is located at the head of Diamond Creek canyon in a small side canyon. Spring can be accessed by hiking or helicopter.
SiteDescription: Riparian vegetation is abundant throughout this side canyon and mostly consists of cottonwood trees. Water emerges from approximately 30 feet above the creek bed and is surrounded by dense hanging gardens. Water is dispersed from three major discharges that combine into one flow at the base of the creek bed. The combined flow measurement of the major discharges is approximately 100 gallons per minute. The site is very isolated and remote and appears that wildlife only access the site on occasion. Springs emerge from base of dolomite band, (base of muav, in bright angel shale); a gushet spring pouring 20m down into a flooded, rocky stream channel.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10M DEM

SiteDescription: Meriwhitica Spring issues from the floor of Meriwhitica Canyon at an elevation of 2655 feet. The canyon is dammed by travertine deposits some 150 feet high, and alluvial sediments fill the canyon behind the dam. The spring surfaces from the alluvium at the south side of the valley about 1500 feet west of the dam and flows across the valley for approximately 1/4 mile parallel to the dam. As recently as 15 years ago water skirted the dam through a steep canyon along the north wall of the canyon. This is now dry, and water soaks back into the alluvium without any obvious spill over the dam or re-emergence along the dry canyon below the dam. The actual source of the water cannot be determined, as it lies under 100 feet or more of alluvium. A well developed streamside riparian plant community grows along the stream, dominated by cottonwood trees.
Georef_Comments: coordinates estimated from DEMs and AGIC data files

AccessDescript: The site is located about 7 miles south east of Peach Springs on the western slope of a small ravine.
SiteDescription: This site is located about 7 miles south east of Peach Springs on the western slope of a small ravine. The emergence of water comes from a small seep at the back of a 40-foot long cave. The bottom of the cave is filled with water and the depth decreases as water approaches the entrance. The walls of this cave have been reinforced by support beams to prevent subsidence and potential loss of this water source. The water here has been utilized to provide livestock with drinking water. This was accomplished by tapping water from the cave to a 3000-gallon storage tank at the bottom of this ravine using PVC pipe. This tank in turn feeds a concrete water trough. Presently, this system is no longer in use as the amount of water needed to run this system is not available, most likely due to drought.

The groundwater channel is a lengthy karst system, one of many in this section of Grand Canyon, that delivers water from the North Rim into the Colorado River.

AccessDescript: The site is located in a small canyon in the Granite Park area on the Hualapai Reservation.
SiteDescription: Water emerges from the back of a 4-foot wide cavern that extends for an unknown distance, but is at least 25 feet long. The area around the spring site has been fenced off as part of a project to enhance the vegetation. About 100 yards of fence was used to fence of the entrance to the canyon. A drinking water system for wildlife has been set up at this site; the components of this system include a primary 150-gallon capture tank that feeds another 150-gallon trough, which is fed through 150 yards of PVC pipe.
Georef_Comments: coordinates estimated from DEMs and AGIC data files

SiteDescription: Milkweed Spring issues from cracks in basalt bedrock and forms a free-flowing stream 3-6 meters wide.  The canyon is very wide with water running through alternating shallow pools. An irregular basalt surface is prevalent.  Large mounds of watercress and filamentous algae fill some of the deeper pools. Sedges and watercress grow where there is coarse submerged soil.  There has been considerable disturbance in the past from settlement, ranch development, and cattle. At the lower end of the ranch area, about 1/4 mile below the spring, there is a low dam. It is utilized for cultural and recreational activities, as well as a source of water for cattle and wildlife. The spring flows year round and aquatic vegetation prevails along the stream.

InfoSourceDet: Imported in 2009 from AZ State Land Office

AccessDescript: The spring site is located along the floor of Peach Springs Wash about 5 miles north of the community of Peach Springs in the Hualapai Reservation.
SiteDescription: The main spring area is fenced off from livestock, and water feeds into an old concrete trough. Cattails grow in the trough and desert wetland species grow below trough in outflow. A saline seep is recognized on the wall of the canyon upstream from the trough. A continuous flow of water discharges from the old concrete trough. Cutting down non-native Tamarisk trees and planting native Goodings Willows and Peach trees have enhanced the spring site. Water flows down Peach Springs Canyon and collects in a dam approximately  of a mile north of the spring. The dam has substantial wetland vegetation around the water and is utilized for swimming and picnics in the summer.

AccessDescript: The site is 7 miles upstream from Colorado River, canyon on river right, approx. 1.5 hours up canyon. Access requires multiple climbs and a hand line is required.

AccessDescript: Go on 423 and turn right on 236 at 363923X and 4054608Y. Go 40 m and turn south on 201.  Go on 201 for 1.2mi, then turn R(west) on 201A. Then go 3.7 mi on 201A (almost to end).  Pack trail seems to start at 358255X and 4054296Y. Follow pack trail north, 675 m to Little Spring. Follow the drainage downstream on the south side. Cross to the north side just above Boulder Spring. The site is about 100 meters downstream from here, at the confluence.
SiteDescription: This steep hypocrenic spring is a precipate-covered mound that emerges from the Hermit Shale at the base of a steep talus slope. The groundwater flow is distinct from that in Little Canyon.
Georef_Comments: Coordinates from DRG, elevation from DEM. GPS elevation 1385 meters.

AccessDescript: The spring is located in Mohawk Canyon and can be accessed by hiking or by helicopter. The spring is up a small side canyon about 1/4 mile west of the upper Mohawk Canyon floor.
SiteDescription: The spring flows year round and is a source of water for wild horses and wildlife. It sits at an elevation of 5200 feet, where the Coconino Sandstone and Hermit Shale contact. There is a series of seven seeps along the base of sandstone cliff, flowing on to a shelf 3-5 meters wide and 10-15 meters long. The spring was developed over 50 years ago with mud plaster rock walls to hold water. A pipe takes a small amount of water from one spring outlet to the edges of the slope. Water soaks into the ground below the shelf.

AccessDescript: From junction 22 (west side road) and 423 (377679X, 4059394Y). Turn west on 423 and go 1.7 mi to 235. Turn right on 235 and go west 7 mi to 267. Turn northwest at 368526X 4058167Y onto 267. On 267, go 2.8 mi. At 365063X and 4059998Y, turn southwest on 267C. Go 3.4 mi to the end of the road. Near the end of the road, a pack trail heads northeast and into the drainage, and passes by Slide spring. Follow drainage down into Slide Canyon, and downstream to the confluence with a canyon entering from the North (about 1 km). Follow this canyon upstream about .75 km. The coordinates to this spring are on canyon right. Confidence is low. Elevation difference to confluence from rim 330 m, and upstream to spring 160 m.

AccessDescript: Pack Trail route: Turn on right on 425 (380257X, 4044237Y) and go west 7.5 mi to 233.  On 233 go about 8.5 m.  From Sowats Point trail, follow trail to Esplanade.  Go cross-country to tributary east of 4544T on map and drop into that tributary. Join main channel and follow that upstream to spring (past at least one other spring on the way). Route is about 7 km, and 465 m elevation, but on trail through the steep section.                                                             Non-trail route - Turn on right on 425 (380257X, 4044237Y) and go west 7.5 mi to 233.  On 233 go 5 mi to 657. At 368291Xand 4040708Y, turn R(north) on 657. Go 0.2mi to 9042w. At 368239X and 4041014Y, turn west on 9042w and go 1.4 mi to wilderness boundary. Coordinates at trailhead: 366383X, 4041354Y. Follow trail to west, then north for 2.4 km. At 365009X, 4042598Y, follow drainage west.  Spring is 2.2 km down this drainage. Elevation difference is 550 m, and drainage looks steep.
SiteDescription: Coordinates for this site were provided by Larry Stevens. The spring discharges from colluvium on a drainage channel bank.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from LES and DRG. GCT's UTMs are 362784 East and 4042847 North.

AccessDescript: Off the Tonto Trail. The Cottonwood Creek site is 14.1 km northeast of, and 860 m below, Grand Canyon Village, and is accessible via the Grandview and Tonto Trails. Cottonwood Creek is a quasi-perennial stream that is fed by numerous sources in the Redwall Formation and the Cambrian strata. The largest single flow appears to be one that issues from beneath a pile of boulders near the topmost Fremont cottonwood tree in the drainage. The stream flows approximately 2 km from the gauge to the Colorado River.
Georef_Comments: Q was measured at the NPS gauge.  Location was determined with GIS.  Samples collected and Q measured near Tonto trail crossing in lower Bright Angel alluvium.  LAT Net Section 32, T31N, R04E.

AccessDescript: Hike into Cottonwood Spring area, go down one of side drainages to join main Cottonwood drainage.  Spring is about 20-30 min. hike downstream just above a nearly technical pouroff that can be bypassed with difficulty on left.  We did not attempt this.  The hike into cottonwood starts at the Tuckup canyon Trailhead.
SiteDescription: Emergence at the site described as, " Canyon bottom with bedrock channel with pools, slides, pouroffs and hanging gardens.  Some fluvial deposits but mostly bedrock.  Supai - Wescogame, Rheochrene and Hanging garden spring type."    Channel length is 190m
Georef_Comments: NPS Coordinates were NAD83 12 329580E 4022289N.  Elevation was 1164 Meters With the following note: In deep canyon - added 8 m to easting as offset correction

AccessDescript: From US-180 turn onto Snow Bowl Rd (NF-516) and travel north for 5.3 mi. Turn left onto Alpenglow Rd for 1.2 mi, and right on Hart Prairie Rd for 1 mi. Hike 1200 m east.
SiteDescription: This site was imported from the SSI geodatabase, a compilation from multiple sources. According to a 2006 paper in Water Resources Research, the Hart Prairie area has the largest Bebb willow (Salix bebbiana) community in the US, yet greater than 95% of willows are older than 80 years and regeneration is not occurring. Low recruitment has been linked to inadequate moisture. The hydrogeology consists of small perched aquifers; recharge is directly related to annual precipitation.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from DEM

SiteDescription: Jeff Hink reports that Oquer Lake is a natural wetland that is fenced. Although the fence appears to be intact, there is evidence of recent impacts from livestock. Riparian vegetation includes Juncus, Carex, broad leaved pondweed, reedgrass, and short and tall spike rush. Water elevation is approximately 12 horizontal (2.5 vertical) feet below wetland extent.

AccessDescript: From junction of Hwy 67 and West Side Rd, north 3.6 miles. Go west on Oquer Canyon Rd. In 1.2 miles turn south on 462. In 2 miles turn east on 765G. In .4 miles turn left on 3564. Road ends in .16 miles. Spring is 100 meters off the end of this road. 765 is driveable.
SiteDescription: Along with Pair Springs South, this was included in the Brown and Moran study. They are in a relatively low gradient area, and are not marked on the DRG, nor are they included on any other layer. No evidence of a spring was found during an intensive search on 6/25/11.
Georef_Comments: Elevation from 10m DEM, coordinates from Brown and Moran
